# Code Changes MUST Be Accompanied by Automated Tests

## Policy

Every code change MUST include automated tests. This applies to:
new features, bug fixes, behavior-changing refactors, business rule changes, and execution flow changes.

## Hard Stop — Do NOT Finalize If:

- No new/updated tests exist for the change
- Tests don't exercise the altered behavior directly
- Tests wouldn't fail if the change were reverted
- Test suite was not executed
- New code has zero coverage
- Exception used without adequate technical justification

If any condition is true: stop, create/fix tests, re-run validation.

## Traceability

Each change MUST have at least one test that:
- Executes the altered code directly
- Explicitly validates the introduced/fixed behavior
- Fails if the change is removed

Indirect, generic, or unrelated tests are NOT sufficient.

## Minimum Coverage by Change Type

**Bugfix**: 1 test reproducing the bug + 1 validating the fix.
**New feature**: 1 happy path test + at least 1 edge case or error test.
**Refactor**: All existing tests pass; add tests if behavior changes.
**Config change** (runtime impact): at least 1 integration test.

Superficial coverage is NOT acceptable.

## Test Strategy

Use the most appropriate level: unit (preferred) > integration > e2e.
Tests must be deterministic, isolated (mocks/stubs when applicable), and fast.

## TDD

When possible, follow Red → Green → Refactor. If not using TDD, justify explicitly.

## Required Evidence

For each change, record:
- Test files created/modified
- Test names added
- Scenarios covered (happy path, errors, edge cases)
- Execution result (pass/fail)

Without this evidence the task is incomplete.

## Regression Protection

Every bugfix MUST include a test reproducing the original problem.

## Exception Policy (Restricted)

Changes without tests are allowed ONLY when technically infeasible:
- Non-versioned one-off scripts
- Irreversible migrations tightly coupled to external state
- Purely visual changes with no verifiable logic impact
- Code dependent exclusively on non-simulable external factors

When claiming an exception, MUST:
1. Justify why tests are not applicable
2. Explain why mocks/stubs/integration alternatives are not viable
3. Describe risks of missing tests
4. Indicate how to validate manually

Unacceptable justifications: "not necessary", "simple change", "low impact", "no time".

## Completion Checklist

- [ ] Test directly linked to the change exists
- [ ] Test would fail without the change
- [ ] Coverage includes success + at least one error scenario
- [ ] Tests were executed
- [ ] All tests are passing
- [ ] Evidence was recorded

ALL items above are required. Without them the task is NOT complete.
